analysis:
This is an absolute robbery. Daylight robbery. And jamesclarkson96 - let's call him "The Charity Case" - has just donated his season to BigBishAl76, who we'll call "The Vulture" because he's picked the bones clean off a struggling manager.

Look at the facts. Week 11, you're sat there in 14th place out of 16, your power score is embarrassing at 29.5, and what do you do? You give away James Cook - a proven RB1 in his prime who's averaging nearly 15 points per game over 45 games - for spare parts. Jauan Jennings? He's a WR3 on his best day. Kimani Vidal? A rookie who's already declining, dropping from 13.2 to 9.9 points after the trade. And Cook? He explodes for 21.3 PPG after you ship him out. That's not bad luck, that's bad management. You've lost 5,528 in value and nearly 5 points off your power score. At what point do you look in the mirror and ask yourself what you're doing?

Meanwhile, The Vulture sits at #2 in the league with a 60.5 power score and he's done what winners do - he's identified weakness and exploited it ruthlessly. He's given up depth pieces he doesn't need for a genuine difference-maker. His power score jumps up 4.6 points. That's how you compete. That's how you push for championships. He understood the fundamentals: running backs win leagues, and he got a premium one for peanuts.

Here's my bold prediction for two years from now: Cook will still be a top-15 back putting up RB1 numbers, Jennings will be a forgotten depth piece fighting for targets, and Vidal will be lucky to have a job. The Charity Case will still be wondering why he can't compete, and The Vulture will have a trophy on his mantle. Sometimes in fantasy football, like in real football, you get what you deserve. And this manager deserved exactly what he got - nothing.
